WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.976 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:01.976 --> 00:00:19.574 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.574 --> 00:00:20.990 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH:
Raise your hand

00:00:20.990 --> 00:00:23.980 align:middle line:84%
if you have a firm
understanding of the economy.

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:25.710 align:middle line:90%
I didn't raise mine either.

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:28.270 align:middle line:10%
From my vantage point, it
seems like one big charade,

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:30.600 align:middle line:10%
a source of infotainment
for the evening news

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:31.830 align:middle line:10%
and cable channels.

00:00:31.830 --> 00:00:34.370 align:middle line:10%
Yet for many, if not most
of us, our money situation

00:00:34.370 --> 00:00:36.480 align:middle line:10%
causes far more
pain than pleasure.

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:38.820 align:middle line:10%
This means we are now
on a need to know basis

00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:40.310 align:middle line:10%
as to what's going on.

00:00:40.310 --> 00:00:43.580 align:middle line:84%
Toward that end, I've
invited Ranting Andy Hoffman

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:46.360 align:middle line:84%
to help us work our way through
the maze of how the world's

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:48.630 align:middle line:84%
economies were brought
to the brink of collapse.

00:00:48.630 --> 00:00:51.340 align:middle line:84%
And what we can do about
it, if anything, now.

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:53.030 align:middle line:84%
And I want to thank
you for joining us.

00:00:53.030 --> 00:00:54.940 align:middle line:90%
This is critical information.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:57.690 align:middle line:84%
You spent 15 to 20 years
as a Wall Street analyst.

00:00:57.690 --> 00:00:59.940 align:middle line:84%
And some of the people that
are in the headlines today

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:01.700 align:middle line:90%
were your former bosses.

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:03.580 align:middle line:90%
So you know what the game is.

00:01:03.580 --> 00:01:06.732 align:middle line:84%
And I love what you
do on your blog.

00:01:06.732 --> 00:01:08.190 align:middle line:84%
Because you don't
pull any punches.

00:01:08.190 --> 00:01:10.320 align:middle line:84%
But you do such a
beautiful job of tying

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:13.200 align:middle line:84%
what seem disparate
bits of economic news

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:17.375 align:middle line:84%
together to see where this
whole thing is flowing badly.

00:01:17.375 --> 00:01:18.250 align:middle line:90%
>>ANDY HOFFMAN: Yeah.

00:01:18.250 --> 00:01:20.069 align:middle line:84%
Well, what I learned--
the one thing

00:01:20.069 --> 00:01:21.610 align:middle line:84%
I got from Wall
Street that's helpful

00:01:21.610 --> 00:01:24.080 align:middle line:90%
these days is communication.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:26.690 align:middle line:84%
But after that, it's
completely different.

00:01:26.690 --> 00:01:29.460 align:middle line:10%
I've almost become-- I don't
want to say a whistle blower,

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:32.970 align:middle line:10%
but a crusader
against what I saw.

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:34.820 align:middle line:10%
I left the industry in 2005.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:36.670 align:middle line:10%
In fact, I was with
Salomon Smith Barney,

00:01:36.670 --> 00:01:40.670 align:middle line:10%
which is a Citigroup
company, for seven years.

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:44.070 align:middle line:84%
And I learned more about
the bad side of Wall Street

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:45.260 align:middle line:90%
than I could imagine.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:46.820 align:middle line:84%
And the funny thing
is, what happened

00:01:46.820 --> 00:01:50.050 align:middle line:84%
back then was nothing
compared to what we see today.

00:01:50.050 --> 00:01:50.980 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I know.

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:51.840 align:middle line:90%
Sad.

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:52.879 align:middle line:90%
Sadly but true.

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:54.170 align:middle line:10%
You know what I thought I'd do.

00:01:54.170 --> 00:01:55.920 align:middle line:10%
I have this little
list of questions here.

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:58.980 align:middle line:10%
Because we literally could
talk for 8 or 10 hours

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:01.740 align:middle line:10%
and barely unravel
what's going on.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:05.340 align:middle line:10%
But I thought what we'd do
is maybe start back 1929,

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:08.690 align:middle line:10%
runs on the bank, what
the world was like.

00:02:08.690 --> 00:02:14.510 align:middle line:84%
What the context of this was
like in a country that was

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:18.560 align:middle line:84%
not-- it wasn't-- our economies
weren't so global at the time.

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:21.427 align:middle line:84%
What was it then and then
lead forward from there.

00:02:21.427 --> 00:02:23.260 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, back
then the United States

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:25.440 align:middle line:84%
was an emerging
power in the world.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:27.390 align:middle line:84%
We were also on a
gold standard, as was

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:28.950 align:middle line:90%
much of the rest of the world.

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:30.760 align:middle line:84%
So what you saw was
what you got when

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:32.650 align:middle line:90%
it came to economic activity.

00:02:32.650 --> 00:02:34.400 align:middle line:10%
The Federal Reserve
had just been

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:36.490 align:middle line:10%
created about 15 years before.

00:02:36.490 --> 00:02:39.930 align:middle line:10%
So there really was no real
debt load yet to speak of.

00:02:39.930 --> 00:02:44.000 align:middle line:84%
And it didn't take
long from 1913

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.680 align:middle line:84%
until the roaring '20s for
the banks to do what they do,

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:51.570 align:middle line:84%
which is to promote
debt and speculation.

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:53.490 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the
roaring '20s was.

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:54.920 align:middle line:90%
It was not a change in mindset.

00:02:54.920 --> 00:02:57.700 align:middle line:84%
It was an increase in wealth
created by the same banker

00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:01.330 align:middle line:84%
games they're playing today,
only on a much lesser level.

00:03:01.330 --> 00:03:04.420 align:middle line:84%
By the time we got to the late
'20s, remember markets were not

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:05.960 align:middle line:90%
manipulated back then.

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So there were no
government means

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:11.180 align:middle line:90%
of trying to alter perception.

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:13.380 align:middle line:84%
And you know, we
had a market crash,

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:14.885 align:middle line:84%
which is what
happens in markets.

00:03:14.885 --> 00:03:17.880 align:middle line:84%
It has nothing to do with
whether it's boom or bust.

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:18.990 align:middle line:90%
They happen.

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:22.030 align:middle line:84%
In that particular time, it was
the United States' first period

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:25.060 align:middle line:84%
of rampant banker
funded speculation.

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:27.880 align:middle line:84%
So it really took
the world by storm.

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:30.049 align:middle line:84%
And when it happened,
the government

00:03:30.049 --> 00:03:31.090 align:middle line:90%
didn't know how to react.

00:03:31.090 --> 00:03:32.390 align:middle line:90%
Banks were closing.

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:35.140 align:middle line:90%
And there was no backup system.

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:36.590 align:middle line:90%
There was really no plan at all.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:39.660 align:middle line:84%
So it took 20 years or
so to get out of that.

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:42.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's a misnomer that
the war helped end it.

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:43.380 align:middle line:90%
It really didn't.

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:45.810 align:middle line:84%
If anything, the war helped
the United States simply

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:49.370 align:middle line:84%
because all of our competitors
overseas destroyed themselves.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:50.870 align:middle line:90%
That's how we came to power.

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:55.480 align:middle line:84%
And you know, but
after the crash,

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:57.690 align:middle line:84%
they created things like
the Glass Steagall Act.

00:03:57.690 --> 00:03:59.565 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I was just
going to ask that, yeah.

00:03:59.565 --> 00:04:01.520 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: To stop
banks from speculating

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:02.980 align:middle line:90%
with people's money.

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.270 align:middle line:90%
And you know, that--

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:08.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Explain the
Glass Steagall Act to us

00:04:08.370 --> 00:04:10.490 align:middle line:84%
in kindergarten
terms, so we really

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:12.490 align:middle line:84%
understand what they
were trying to do

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:14.680 align:middle line:84%
and what happened
when, essentially, we

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:16.667 align:middle line:84%
moved away from that
about 20 years ago.

00:04:16.667 --> 00:04:17.250 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: OK.

00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:20.440 align:middle line:84%
Well, in today's world, you
only hear the word banks.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:23.400 align:middle line:84%
They may be referred to as mega
banks, too big to fail banks,

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:25.290 align:middle line:84%
but you only hear
the word banks.

00:04:25.290 --> 00:04:27.830 align:middle line:84%
But even 10 years ago,
let alone back then,

00:04:27.830 --> 00:04:30.590 align:middle line:84%
there were what you call
commercial banks and investment

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:31.230 align:middle line:90%
banks.

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:33.820 align:middle line:84%
Now a commercial bank is
what you think a bank as.

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.670 align:middle line:84%
You put in your money, that
you borrow money from them.

00:04:37.670 --> 00:04:38.870 align:middle line:90%
They take your deposits.

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:41.970 align:middle line:84%
And they supposedly invest
them into safe securities,

00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:44.320 align:middle line:84%
almost like an insurance
company would do.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And they're supposedly
safe, you know.

00:04:48.270 --> 00:04:50.640 align:middle line:84%
They're there
almost as non-profit

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:51.527 align:middle line:90%
for the neighborhood.

00:04:51.527 --> 00:04:53.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So if you
need-- so the point was,

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:54.960 align:middle line:84%
there had been a
run on the banks.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:57.410 align:middle line:84%
We had this disaster
economically.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is to ensure
that you, as a depositor,

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:02.150 align:middle line:84%
can go and get your
money out of the bank

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:03.570 align:middle line:90%
safely at any given time.

00:05:03.570 --> 00:05:03.780 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Right.

00:05:03.780 --> 00:05:05.590 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It's supposed
to be a guarantee, right.

00:05:05.590 --> 00:05:07.881 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: But the difference
between a commercial bank

00:05:07.881 --> 00:05:11.250 align:middle line:84%
and an investment bank, and
again Solomon Smith Barney

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:14.720 align:middle line:84%
was an investment bank, today
it would just be called a bank,

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:17.480 align:middle line:90%
but that's the misnomer.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:18.710 align:middle line:90%
They call it investment bank.

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:20.240 align:middle line:84%
But it's not really
a bank at all.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:22.200 align:middle line:90%
It's a speculation machine.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:26.450 align:middle line:84%
Their primary business
is IPOs like Facebook.

00:05:26.450 --> 00:05:28.090 align:middle line:84%
That's what they
do for a living.

00:05:28.090 --> 00:05:30.470 align:middle line:84%
They also have what they call
proprietary trading, which

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:32.880 align:middle line:84%
simply means they gamble
with their own money.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:35.120 align:middle line:84%
They don't have
deposits, just people

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:36.520 align:middle line:90%
who have brokerage accounts.

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:38.540 align:middle line:84%
So it's a completely
different animal.

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:41.980 align:middle line:84%
It has nothing to do with
what a traditional bank is.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:45.550 align:middle line:84%
And until the roaring
'20s, the banks

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:48.020 align:middle line:84%
just did the former,
what I was talking about.

00:05:48.020 --> 00:05:49.340 align:middle line:90%
They just lent money.

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:49.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:51.703 align:middle line:10%
But then the banks after
the Federal Reserve

00:05:51.703 --> 00:05:54.420 align:middle line:10%
came around and started to get
control of the money supply,

00:05:54.420 --> 00:05:58.700 align:middle line:10%
and the government, they
started to speculate.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:01.160 align:middle line:10%
And that's what
caused the crash then.

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:04.540 align:middle line:84%
So after the crash,
Glass Steagall

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:07.300 align:middle line:84%
was created to separate
those two things.

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:09.200 align:middle line:84%
So if you want to
be a speculator,

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.970 align:middle line:90%
you are an investment bank.

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:14.970 align:middle line:84%
You can't be part
of the FDIC system.

00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:17.590 align:middle line:84%
You have to be your
own financial company.

00:06:17.590 --> 00:06:20.420 align:middle line:84%
That has nothing to do
with government backing.

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:24.120 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we saw proliferate

00:06:24.120 --> 00:06:31.110 align:middle line:84%
from the '20s through 1999, when
Glass Steagall was repealed.

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:36.090 align:middle line:84%
So you saw these huge growth
in these non-bank banks.

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:37.990 align:middle line:84%
And then when they
got powerful enough,

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:39.930 align:middle line:84%
they were able to
lobby the government

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:43.250 align:middle line:84%
during the good times
of 1999 when internet--

00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:45.060 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah,
the roaring '90s.

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:47.560 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah, saying well
look at great everything is.

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:50.410 align:middle line:84%
We don't need to
have this separation.

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:53.330 align:middle line:90%
Plus we're going to buy you.

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:56.710 align:middle line:84%
Because you know who had the
most campaign contributions

00:06:56.710 --> 00:07:00.700 align:middle line:84%
for Bush in 2000 and
2004, Obama in 2008,

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:03.462 align:middle line:84%
and Mit Romney in 2012,
is from Wall Street.

00:07:03.462 --> 00:07:04.420 align:middle line:90%
They kind of took over.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:07.080 align:middle line:84%
And you see the people
who took over positions

00:07:07.080 --> 00:07:11.532 align:middle line:84%
of off-- Robert Rubin, Secretary
of the Treasury, Tim Geithner.

00:07:11.532 --> 00:07:12.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Tim Geithner, yeah.

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:15.520 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: All these guys,
they come from Wall Street.

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:17.950 align:middle line:84%
Obama's just had
the Chief of Staff

00:07:17.950 --> 00:07:21.100 align:middle line:84%
was William Daley, who was a
managing director at JP Morgan,

00:07:21.100 --> 00:07:23.050 align:middle line:84%
and before that
Rahm Emanuel, who

00:07:23.050 --> 00:07:25.210 align:middle line:84%
worked for Goldman Sachs
and all these guys.

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So the point is, they kind
of took over the system

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:31.412 align:middle line:84%
and convinced, through campaign
contributions, people like Bill

00:07:31.412 --> 00:07:33.620 align:middle line:84%
Clinton and the senators
who were around in the '90s,

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:34.960 align:middle line:90%
that we don't need this.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:37.094 align:middle line:84%
And when they got
rid of it in 1999,

00:07:37.094 --> 00:07:38.510 align:middle line:84%
that was the
beginning of the end.

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:41.180 align:middle line:84%
On top of that, that
was also the end

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:43.800 align:middle line:84%
of a kind of upswing
in the economy.

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:46.125 align:middle line:84%
So you had the banks getting
more lethal at a time

00:07:46.125 --> 00:07:47.625 align:middle line:84%
where the economy
was getting worse.

00:07:47.625 --> 00:07:51.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So In 1999,
the Glass Steagall

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:53.130 align:middle line:90%
was repealed in essence.

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:59.390 align:middle line:84%
And so now does that mean
that the FDIC was covering

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:01.830 align:middle line:84%
both the wild investment,
the investment

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:03.300 align:middle line:90%
banks, and the commercial banks?

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:04.420 align:middle line:90%
They're liable for both?

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:04.920 align:middle line:90%
I mean--

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:06.295 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: They
created something

00:08:06.295 --> 00:08:09.600 align:middle line:84%
called SIPC, Securities
Income Protection, which

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:12.740 align:middle line:84%
is like FDIC for
brokerages accounts.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:14.580 align:middle line:84%
So again, this is
the kind of things

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:16.270 align:middle line:90%
that bankers get accomplished.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:17.650 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: But this isn't right.

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:20.530 align:middle line:84%
The government should not be
paying for gambling debts.

00:08:20.530 --> 00:08:21.960 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: That's exactly right.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:26.050 align:middle line:84%
But when the bankers own the
government, and they truly do,

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:27.553 align:middle line:90%
they get whatever they want.

00:08:27.553 --> 00:08:28.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:31.927 align:middle line:84%
So that leads us
up to 2007, 2008.

00:08:31.927 --> 00:08:33.760 align:middle line:84%
Now there were some big
bumps along the way.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:36.520 align:middle line:84%
It's not like we haven't
seen difficult times before.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:40.150 align:middle line:84%
Early 1980s, god I remember
when interest rates on homes

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:42.700 align:middle line:90%
were at 14 and 15%, even higher.

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:45.490 align:middle line:84%
And then we had the savings
and loan debacle as well.

00:08:45.490 --> 00:08:48.930 align:middle line:84%
What was happening during
that little period, as opposed

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:51.180 align:middle line:90%
to what's happening now?

00:08:51.180 --> 00:08:53.810 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, that period
was just after the gold standard

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:56.280 align:middle line:90%
had come off, which was 1971.

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:59.130 align:middle line:84%
So again, the nation
didn't have a lot of debt.

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:00.810 align:middle line:84%
And it's no coincidence
that the nation

00:09:00.810 --> 00:09:03.530 align:middle line:84%
didn't have a lot
of debt until 1971.

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:06.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're at the public
debt that's announced

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:08.310 align:middle line:90%
today is $16 trillion dollars.

00:09:08.310 --> 00:09:11.460 align:middle line:84%
It was about $200 or
$300 billion back then.

00:09:11.460 --> 00:09:14.152 align:middle line:84%
And that was from
200 years of history.

00:09:14.152 --> 00:09:15.860 align:middle line:84%
That's because the
gold standard does not

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:18.640 align:middle line:84%
allow you to build up debt
without having a commensurate

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:19.930 align:middle line:90%
increase in gold.

00:09:19.930 --> 00:09:24.760 align:middle line:84%
So when-- in the
1970s, the government

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:27.450 align:middle line:84%
could print all the money it
wanted to get out of things.

00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:29.420 align:middle line:84%
And it could raise
interest rates.

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:32.040 align:middle line:84%
Because unlike now, where
we have all this debt

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:35.740 align:middle line:84%
across the entire
system, it could

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:38.100 align:middle line:90%
take higher interest rates here.

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:39.626 align:middle line:90%
They're at zero right now.

00:09:39.626 --> 00:09:42.000 align:middle line:84%
Some countries have just gone
to negative interest rates.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.250 align:middle line:84%
They literally can't
afford even a tiny increase

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:45.470 align:middle line:90%
in interest rates.

00:09:45.470 --> 00:09:48.080 align:middle line:84%
Of course, low interest
rates is bad for savers.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:49.840 align:middle line:90%
No one wants money in the bank.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:54.680 align:middle line:84%
And again, a backup on your
question, in the '70s it

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:57.780 align:middle line:84%
was really a cyclical
downturn, which

00:09:57.780 --> 00:10:01.350 align:middle line:84%
was exacerbated by political
tensions in the Middle East

00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:03.590 align:middle line:90%
that caused oil prices to go up.

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:07.660 align:middle line:84%
So it was really more
of a regular downturn

00:10:07.660 --> 00:10:09.139 align:middle line:90%
that got exacerbated.

00:10:09.139 --> 00:10:09.680 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:12.640 align:middle line:84%
And then you had the
savings and loan scandals

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:15.214 align:middle line:84%
that took place in the
'80s, right, on top of that.

00:10:15.214 --> 00:10:15.880 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah.

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:18.200 align:middle line:84%
And the savings
and loan scandals

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:20.670 align:middle line:84%
were more of a function
of just shoddy bank

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:23.210 align:middle line:84%
practices than
something more sinister.

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:25.100 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there were some
bad people involved.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:26.960 align:middle line:84%
But again, they had the
savings and bank loan.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:29.293 align:middle line:84%
They created the-- I forgot
what the name of that agency

00:10:29.293 --> 00:10:31.110 align:middle line:90%
was-- to clean it up.

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:31.870 align:middle line:90%
And they did.

00:10:31.870 --> 00:10:34.420 align:middle line:84%
Because again, it was
clean up-able back then.

00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:37.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It was clean up-able
and fairly isolated in a sense.

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:40.500 align:middle line:84%
And it took a few years, not
too long, to recover from that,

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:41.560 align:middle line:90%
as I recall.

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:44.640 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Right, it
really was not a big deal

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.990 align:middle line:84%
for the majority of the
public, and certainly

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:49.090 align:middle line:84%
was not felt anywhere
around the world.

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:51.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, so then we're
back to the free market.

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:51.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:53.740 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
the free market.

00:10:53.740 --> 00:10:56.330 align:middle line:84%
It sounds from everything
I'm hearing, and certainly

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:59.490 align:middle line:84%
the subtext, and the direct
text of what you say,

00:10:59.490 --> 00:11:02.419 align:middle line:84%
we don't really
have free markets.

00:11:02.419 --> 00:11:04.460 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, we don't--
in the United States,

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:06.300 align:middle line:90%
we have zero free markets.

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:08.650 align:middle line:90%
And I mean utter zero.

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:10.300 align:middle line:84%
In fact, there are
actually names.

00:11:10.300 --> 00:11:13.440 align:middle line:84%
And part of what I do is I'm
pointing out the obvious.

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.630 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people think
well, you're so smart.

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:17.100 align:middle line:84%
You're so tuned
into these things.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:18.760 align:middle line:84%
I go, you know, I'm
just telling you

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:20.570 align:middle line:90%
what's the public information.

00:11:20.570 --> 00:11:22.750 align:middle line:84%
The Federal Reserve
manipulates bonds

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:26.870 align:middle line:84%
with what they call quantitative
easing, operation twist.

00:11:26.870 --> 00:11:30.090 align:middle line:84%
The ECB calls it long term
refinancing operations.

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:32.030 align:middle line:90%
They call it the swap agreement.

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:35.490 align:middle line:84%
The fact is they are in business
to buy bonds and manipulate

00:11:35.490 --> 00:11:36.340 align:middle line:90%
the market.

00:11:36.340 --> 00:11:39.640 align:middle line:84%
There's also a public
group created in 1987

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.940 align:middle line:84%
by Ronald Reagan right after
the crash, the stock crash,

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:45.570 align:middle line:84%
called the President's Working
Group on Financial Markets.

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:47.090 align:middle line:90%
You can Google it.

00:11:47.090 --> 00:11:48.250 align:middle line:90%
It's very well defined.

00:11:48.250 --> 00:11:52.490 align:middle line:84%
It involves the leaders
of the SEC, and the CFTC,

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:53.740 align:middle line:90%
and banking leaders.

00:11:53.740 --> 00:11:56.550 align:middle line:84%
And their job is to prop
up the stock market.

00:11:56.550 --> 00:11:59.050 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's a
government agency.

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:02.170 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing-- George
Stephanopoulos admitted to it,

00:12:02.170 --> 00:12:04.000 align:middle line:84%
talked about it openly
a few years ago.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:04.850 align:middle line:90%
It's real.

00:12:04.850 --> 00:12:07.960 align:middle line:84%
There's also an organization,
a government organization,

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:09.780 align:middle line:84%
called the Exchange
Stabilization Fund.

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:11.990 align:middle line:90%
It's been around 70, 80 years.

00:12:11.990 --> 00:12:15.090 align:middle line:84%
Its job, its mandate,
is to manipulate

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:16.930 align:middle line:84%
foreign currency
and gold and silver.

00:12:16.930 --> 00:12:18.290 align:middle line:90%
That's what it says.

00:12:18.290 --> 00:12:19.130 align:middle line:90%
So, the fact is--

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:21.089 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: To manipulate--
manage or manipulate.

00:12:21.089 --> 00:12:22.879 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, they
would call it manage.

00:12:22.879 --> 00:12:23.440 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:24.180 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: OK.

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:26.840 align:middle line:84%
But my point is that these
organizations, people call

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:29.280 align:middle line:84%
me a conspiracy
theorist, but I'm not.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:31.340 align:middle line:84%
I'm a scientist when
it comes to finance.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:32.350 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: You're just
calling it like it is.

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:33.110 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah.

00:12:33.110 --> 00:12:34.660 align:middle line:84%
And the fact is in
the United States,

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:37.140 align:middle line:84%
we actually have names
for these organizations.

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:40.262 align:middle line:84%
In Europe, which is
a newer organization,

00:12:40.262 --> 00:12:41.720 align:middle line:84%
they're still trying
to figure out.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:45.270 align:middle line:84%
In fact, every day is a new
reaction to something bad.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:47.370 align:middle line:84%
But because they
have 20 countries,

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:49.420 align:middle line:84%
they don't have
the infrastructure

00:12:49.420 --> 00:12:52.640 align:middle line:84%
to create these organizations
that are formal.

00:12:52.640 --> 00:12:54.980 align:middle line:84%
So they have to meet
every couple of weeks.

00:12:54.980 --> 00:12:57.490 align:middle line:84%
And say well, now we're creating
the long term refinancing

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:59.830 align:middle line:84%
operation, where we
will support bonds.

00:12:59.830 --> 00:13:01.730 align:middle line:84%
Now we'll create
the SMP, which is

00:13:01.730 --> 00:13:07.060 align:middle line:84%
some British term with the
British language with the oldie

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:10.550 align:middle line:84%
and stuff like that to describe
how buy government bonds.

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:12.540 align:middle line:84%
And so these things have
been around forever.

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:14.550 align:middle line:84%
Now when it comes
to gold, which is

00:13:14.550 --> 00:13:18.200 align:middle line:84%
my particular area
of expertise, it's

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:22.110 align:middle line:84%
been manipulated, suppressed,
for the past 1,000, 5,000

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:22.610 align:middle line:90%
years.

00:13:22.610 --> 00:13:24.300 align:middle line:84%
Any time there's
been a government

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:26.460 align:middle line:84%
that wanted to
control the currency,

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:27.810 align:middle line:90%
they suppress the price of gold.

00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:29.070 align:middle line:90%
First they take it.

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:30.395 align:middle line:90%
And then they suppress.

00:13:30.395 --> 00:13:32.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They've
confiscated it in the past.

00:13:32.270 --> 00:13:34.370 align:middle line:84%
And that did happen, I
think, in '33, right?

00:13:34.370 --> 00:13:35.100 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah.

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:37.562 align:middle line:84%
but again, nothing was
actually taken from anyone.

00:13:37.562 --> 00:13:38.520 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No it wasn't.

00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:39.229 align:middle line:90%
Now explain that.

00:13:39.229 --> 00:13:41.894 align:middle line:84%
Because that's what-- you always
read that gold was confiscated.

00:13:41.894 --> 00:13:42.580 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yes.

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:43.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What
actually happened.

00:13:43.360 --> 00:13:44.901 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: It's one
of the few things

00:13:44.901 --> 00:13:47.130 align:middle line:84%
that people who know
nothing seem to know.

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:48.020 align:middle line:90%
And they come at me.

00:13:48.020 --> 00:13:50.185 align:middle line:84%
I won't buy gold because
it was confiscated.

00:13:50.185 --> 00:13:51.770 align:middle line:90%
It will get confiscated again.

00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:56.220 align:middle line:84%
Now in 1933, we were in the
middle of the Great Depression.

00:13:56.220 --> 00:13:59.270 align:middle line:84%
And FDR had just
come into office.

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:01.900 align:middle line:84%
And he put out a
decree that says,

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:06.122 align:middle line:84%
you must give in your gold
for the fixed price of $20.67.

00:14:06.122 --> 00:14:07.830 align:middle line:84%
Because we were still
on a gold standard.

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:08.871 align:middle line:90%
That's what it was worth.

00:14:08.871 --> 00:14:12.030 align:middle line:84%
Now, even before
that decree, there

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:14.100 align:middle line:84%
were public calls
for patriotism.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:15.450 align:middle line:90%
We need to help the country.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:18.420 align:middle line:84%
The country can't-- again,
when you have a gold standard,

00:14:18.420 --> 00:14:21.810 align:middle line:84%
you can't spend like on the
Tennessee Valley Authority

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:23.234 align:middle line:90%
without gold in hand.

00:14:23.234 --> 00:14:23.900 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:24.790 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: That's
the beauty of it.

00:14:24.790 --> 00:14:25.870 align:middle line:90%
You can't create debt.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:27.240 align:middle line:90%
You can't spend without it.

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:30.300 align:middle line:84%
So there were kind of
public calls for patriotism.

00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:33.470 align:middle line:84%
Turn in your gold and
we'll give you money.

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:34.890 align:middle line:90%
And this was before the decree.

00:14:34.890 --> 00:14:36.210 align:middle line:84%
And people gave it
in hand over fist.

00:14:36.210 --> 00:14:36.751 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:14:36.751 --> 00:14:38.260 align:middle line:90%
So this was voluntary.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:39.744 align:middle line:90%
It was the spirit of the times.

00:14:39.744 --> 00:14:40.910 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Before 1933, yes.

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:41.686 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It wasn't
as though you

00:14:41.686 --> 00:14:43.144 align:middle line:84%
had he police
knocking on your door

00:14:43.144 --> 00:14:44.489 align:middle line:90%
taking your gold away from you.

00:14:44.489 --> 00:14:47.030 align:middle line:10%
>>HOFFMAN: And again, at that
time there was a gold standard.

00:14:47.030 --> 00:14:50.690 align:middle line:84%
Every gold-- every dollar
said on it payable to

00:14:50.690 --> 00:14:53.120 align:middle line:90%
for X amount of ounces of gold.

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:54.630 align:middle line:84%
So if the government
said, we really

00:14:54.630 --> 00:14:56.580 align:middle line:90%
need to expand our spending.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:14:58.227 align:middle line:90%
Can you just give us your gold.

00:14:58.227 --> 00:15:00.060 align:middle line:84%
We'll give you dollars
that are gold backed.

00:15:00.060 --> 00:15:01.020 align:middle line:90%
People were like, fine.

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:02.686 align:middle line:84%
We can just get them
back in the future.

00:15:02.686 --> 00:15:04.230 align:middle line:90%
They're gold backed.

00:15:04.230 --> 00:15:08.190 align:middle line:84%
Of course, what he did was
after he made the decree, all

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:11.390 align:middle line:84%
the gold that had been
given to them, they said A,

00:15:11.390 --> 00:15:12.550 align:middle line:90%
you can't have it back.

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:14.270 align:middle line:90%
It's now illegal to own it.

00:15:14.270 --> 00:15:17.000 align:middle line:84%
And B, we're now
valuing at $35 an ounce.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.890 align:middle line:84%
So we get twice the
value that you had.

00:15:19.890 --> 00:15:21.360 align:middle line:90%
And you can't have it back.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.300 align:middle line:84%
So the people learned back
then that the government

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:27.240 align:middle line:84%
is liars, or are
liars, back then.

00:15:27.240 --> 00:15:30.270 align:middle line:84%
Which is-- so and even
after that happened,

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:32.156 align:middle line:90%
they didn't take anyone's gold.

00:15:32.156 --> 00:15:34.530 align:middle line:84%
Even after they said OK, it's
now $35.00 an ounce and you

00:15:34.530 --> 00:15:37.170 align:middle line:84%
can't have it, not a single
ounce was ever taken.

00:15:37.170 --> 00:15:39.050 align:middle line:84%
Even there was some
misnomers that they

00:15:39.050 --> 00:15:41.555 align:middle line:84%
went into safe deposit
box and took them.

00:15:41.555 --> 00:15:42.180 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Hmhm.

00:15:42.180 --> 00:15:42.679 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:15:42.679 --> 00:15:43.720 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: They didn't.

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:46.180 align:middle line:84%
Of course, I would
never put any in a bank.

00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:49.140 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't put a dollar in a
bank, let alone my valuables,

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:50.421 align:middle line:90%
like a gold bar.

00:15:50.421 --> 00:15:51.920 align:middle line:84%
But the fact is
they never took any.

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:53.570 align:middle line:90%
There was actually one lawsuit.

00:15:53.570 --> 00:15:55.700 align:middle line:84%
Someone sued because
the government

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.480 align:middle line:84%
got a hold of their
gold in some kind

00:15:58.480 --> 00:16:00.970 align:middle line:84%
of legal arrange--
legal lawsuit.

00:16:00.970 --> 00:16:02.470 align:middle line:84%
And they said, no
you can't have it.

00:16:02.470 --> 00:16:04.999 align:middle line:84%
The judges said you can't
take the person's gold.

00:16:04.999 --> 00:16:06.790 align:middle line:84%
So no one ever actually
had it confiscated.

00:16:06.790 --> 00:16:09.690 align:middle line:84%
And in today's world,
for a million reasons,

00:16:09.690 --> 00:16:11.756 align:middle line:84%
I think it's insane
to even comprehend.

00:16:11.756 --> 00:16:13.130 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But like
you just said,

00:16:13.130 --> 00:16:14.590 align:middle line:84%
you wouldn't put
money in a vault,

00:16:14.590 --> 00:16:16.835 align:middle line:84%
in a safe deposit
box in the bank.

00:16:16.835 --> 00:16:18.460 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: No, I
wouldn't put anything.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:19.543 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Why, I mean why.

00:16:19.543 --> 00:16:22.360 align:middle line:84%
If it couldn't be confiscated,
why would you not trust them?

00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:24.693 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, I don't trust
the banks for any reasons

00:16:24.693 --> 00:16:27.500 align:middle line:84%
because the banks are the people
who have been stealing from us.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:30.610 align:middle line:84%
And again, the banks and the
government are one in the same.

00:16:30.610 --> 00:16:32.560 align:middle line:84%
And when you say JP
Morgan, like people

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:34.810 align:middle line:84%
say oh, JP Morgan, the
short or the silver?

00:16:34.810 --> 00:16:35.960 align:middle line:90%
It's not JP Morgan.

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:37.170 align:middle line:90%
It's the government.

00:16:37.170 --> 00:16:38.870 align:middle line:84%
And if you have your
stuff in a bank,

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:41.890 align:middle line:84%
that means you're leaving your
possessions in the government's

00:16:41.890 --> 00:16:42.450 align:middle line:90%
hands.

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:45.690 align:middle line:84%
And you know what governments
do with people's possessions.

00:16:45.690 --> 00:16:46.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:46.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:46.990 --> 00:16:49.760 align:middle line:84%
Now-- so we're not
in a-- we're not

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:52.690 align:middle line:84%
participating in a free market
on any level from what you just

00:16:52.690 --> 00:16:53.620 align:middle line:90%
told us, not really.

00:16:53.620 --> 00:16:54.370 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: No, no.

00:16:54.370 --> 00:16:56.130 align:middle line:90%
Some places more than others.

00:16:56.130 --> 00:16:58.070 align:middle line:90%
United States, zero.

00:16:58.070 --> 00:17:00.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And yet we feel
like we have the right

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:04.800 align:middle line:84%
to invest in a stock, or invest
in a bond if we'd like to.

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:06.170 align:middle line:90%
And there's your free market.

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:08.190 align:middle line:90%
We have the freedom to invest.

00:17:08.190 --> 00:17:11.026 align:middle line:84%
And here we have a market
that a little while back,

00:17:11.026 --> 00:17:12.900 align:middle line:84%
a few years ago, it
dropped all the way down,

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:15.430 align:middle line:84%
as I recall to
something like 7,000.

00:17:15.430 --> 00:17:17.310 align:middle line:90%
Now it's back up to 13.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:19.310 align:middle line:84%
And everyone sees if
you just sit on it,

00:17:19.310 --> 00:17:21.390 align:middle line:84%
the free market will
take care of itself.

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:22.589 align:middle line:90%
It's all bounce back.

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:23.755 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Isn't that funny?

00:17:23.755 --> 00:17:25.510 align:middle line:90%
The Dow is up to 13,000.

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:27.589 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, in
real terms, if you

00:17:27.589 --> 00:17:31.740 align:middle line:84%
use what real inflation is,
it's probably down about 70%

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:32.760 align:middle line:90%
in the past 10 years.

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:35.130 align:middle line:84%
If you look at what real
inflation is, and oh,

00:17:35.130 --> 00:17:37.940 align:middle line:84%
by the way, if you include the
four companies that have been

00:17:37.940 --> 00:17:42.400 align:middle line:84%
bankrupted or reorganized,
General Motors, Citigroup, AIG,

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:46.060 align:middle line:84%
and Eastman Kodak, the Dow
would be probably 10,000 and not

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:46.630 align:middle line:90%
13,000.

00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:47.730 align:middle line:90%
But that's just--

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:50.200 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But I mean,
my understanding is also

00:17:50.200 --> 00:17:54.450 align:middle line:84%
that the data on a daily
basis is also manipulated,

00:17:54.450 --> 00:17:57.120 align:middle line:84%
in that the companies that
aren't performing so well

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:58.890 align:middle line:84%
might be taken
out of the listing

00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:01.780 align:middle line:84%
and you edge over the ones that
maybe had a better day just

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:03.530 align:middle line:84%
to prop whatever number
you want up there.

00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:05.450 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: That's what I
mean by GM and Citigroup.

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:05.660 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's it.

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:06.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:06.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:08.165 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: It's a survivor bias.

00:18:08.165 --> 00:18:08.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Survivor bias, OK.

00:18:08.740 --> 00:18:11.380 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: So not only is
the Dow down in real terms,

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:14.050 align:middle line:84%
but if you actually use the
same Dow, it's down also.

00:18:14.050 --> 00:18:15.820 align:middle line:84%
But you know, the
mainstream media,

00:18:15.820 --> 00:18:17.880 align:middle line:84%
which is part of the
machine, their job

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:21.420 align:middle line:84%
is tell you the Dow is 13,000
so you should be happy.

00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:23.860 align:middle line:90%
But the fact is it's 13,000.

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:24.690 align:middle line:90%
Big deal.

00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:27.310 align:middle line:84%
The average, there was just
an article out a few weeks ago

00:18:27.310 --> 00:18:30.670 align:middle line:84%
that says the average median
net worth is down something

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:33.740 align:middle line:84%
like 40% in the
past five years, OK.

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:37.770 align:middle line:84%
So clearly the Dow at 13,000
is not helping people, OK.

00:18:37.770 --> 00:18:40.370 align:middle line:84%
People don't own bond-- you
can't even buy bonds anymore

00:18:40.370 --> 00:18:41.790 align:middle line:90%
because they have no yield.

00:18:41.790 --> 00:18:44.980 align:middle line:84%
Or you could buy a junk
bond and lose your money.

00:18:44.980 --> 00:18:47.740 align:middle line:84%
Or you could buy a
government bond for 0%,

00:18:47.740 --> 00:18:51.150 align:middle line:84%
or in Switzerland for
negative 0.5% and pay them.

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:54.530 align:middle line:84%
So whether you buy or
sell a bond or a stock,

00:18:54.530 --> 00:18:57.390 align:middle line:84%
remember that the government
has a printing press

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:59.540 align:middle line:84%
and is always on the
other side of the trade,

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:02.680 align:middle line:84%
buying what you're selling,
or selling what you're buying.

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:05.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I recommend
people to stay away,

00:19:05.090 --> 00:19:08.280 align:middle line:84%
long or short, from
everything paper.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:09.180 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:19:09.180 --> 00:19:11.570 align:middle line:84%
Now this morning, I
was reading an article

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:16.650 align:middle line:84%
in the paper that was saying in
2007 when the poop hit the fan,

00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:19.810 align:middle line:84%
was there some element
of that was temporarily

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:26.680 align:middle line:84%
reenacted that is it due to go
off December 31st this year?

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:33.050 align:middle line:84%
Or FDIC was to continue its
extending its protections.

00:19:33.050 --> 00:19:34.294 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, what is this.

00:19:34.294 --> 00:19:35.460 align:middle line:90%
You can see what I'm saying.

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:37.120 align:middle line:84%
Because I can't
remember the details.

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:39.020 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: When
that happened, when

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:44.780 align:middle line:84%
what I call Global Meltdown
One occurred in late 2008,

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:47.750 align:middle line:84%
it took the government
by surprise.

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:51.500 align:middle line:84%
They were not prepared for
everything to hit the fan,

00:19:51.500 --> 00:19:54.200 align:middle line:84%
because they thought, hey, we
just repealed Glass Steagall.

00:19:54.200 --> 00:19:55.410 align:middle line:90%
These banks are doing great.

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:58.320 align:middle line:84%
There's a real
state boom going on.

00:19:58.320 --> 00:19:59.120 align:middle line:90%
Everything's well.

00:19:59.120 --> 00:20:00.750 align:middle line:84%
They were in the middle
of an election cycle

00:20:00.750 --> 00:20:02.166 align:middle line:84%
on top of that
where you just talk

00:20:02.166 --> 00:20:03.850 align:middle line:90%
about how great everything is.

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:06.797 align:middle line:84%
So they were taken
by surprise when

00:20:06.797 --> 00:20:08.880 align:middle line:84%
the real estate-- it was
basically the real estate

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:11.220 align:middle line:84%
bubble blowing up
that caused that.

00:20:11.220 --> 00:20:16.170 align:middle line:84%
The derivatives created by
the 1999 repeal of the Glass

00:20:16.170 --> 00:20:19.560 align:middle line:84%
Steagall is what made the
bubble in real estate that

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:21.060 align:middle line:90%
much more lethal.

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:23.500 align:middle line:10%
And so when it came down and
all the derivatives came down

00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:28.370 align:middle line:10%
with it, like AIG for
instance, and Citigroup,

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:30.770 align:middle line:10%
and Bear Stearns,
and Lehman Brothers,

00:20:30.770 --> 00:20:32.740 align:middle line:10%
they were taken by surprise.

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:36.660 align:middle line:10%
So their initial reaction
was just print, print, print.

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:37.610 align:middle line:90%
You can call it tarp.

00:20:37.610 --> 00:20:43.040 align:middle line:84%
You can call it increasing
the size of FDIC and SIPC.

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:47.040 align:middle line:84%
You can call it the
various housing programs

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:50.969 align:middle line:84%
they created to-- with the
first time mortgage, what

00:20:50.969 --> 00:20:52.510 align:middle line:84%
do they call it,
the first time buyer

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:54.520 align:middle line:84%
where you get all
the tax credits.

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:57.080 align:middle line:84%
They were just giving
away money basically.

00:20:57.080 --> 00:21:00.260 align:middle line:84%
And for a couple
years it worked.

00:21:00.260 --> 00:21:03.790 align:middle line:84%
Because people were so shocked
and awed by all the money

00:21:03.790 --> 00:21:04.540 align:middle line:90%
that was printed.

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:06.820 align:middle line:84%
And they ran up the
stock market again,

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:08.940 align:middle line:84%
that they thought
everything was fine.

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:13.520 align:middle line:84%
And then kind of like taking the
painkiller off, once it wears

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:16.464 align:middle line:84%
down, you realize that your
bone is just as broken.

00:21:16.464 --> 00:21:18.380 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it's a lot more
broken because you've

00:21:18.380 --> 00:21:22.150 align:middle line:84%
been walking on this broken
bone for a couple of years.

00:21:22.150 --> 00:21:24.100 align:middle line:90%
And that's where we stand today.

00:21:24.100 --> 00:21:26.550 align:middle line:84%
And all they know how to
do is just give themselves

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:27.450 align:middle line:90%
more drugs.

00:21:27.450 --> 00:21:31.980 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, so essentially
at this time let's talk

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:33.300 align:middle line:90%
about FDIC for moment.

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:36.030 align:middle line:84%
Because I think that's-- with
everything going on, people are

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:37.060 align:middle line:90%
thinking, well jeez.

00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:40.060 align:middle line:84%
At least my savings or
whatever I have left,

00:21:40.060 --> 00:21:41.470 align:middle line:90%
it may not be drawing interest.

00:21:41.470 --> 00:21:43.770 align:middle line:84%
But if one of these
banks collapses,

00:21:43.770 --> 00:21:47.770 align:middle line:84%
I'm still protected
under the FDIC coverage.

00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:50.240 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well that's assuming
the bank is still there.

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:52.730 align:middle line:84%
Because banks tend
to freeze assets.

00:21:52.730 --> 00:21:54.360 align:middle line:84%
You just saw it in
Spain two weeks ago,

00:21:54.360 --> 00:21:55.360 align:middle line:90%
a company called Bankia.

00:21:55.360 --> 00:21:59.245 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the biggest
banks in all of Spain, froze.

00:21:59.245 --> 00:21:59.870 align:middle line:90%
They closed it.

00:21:59.870 --> 00:22:01.310 align:middle line:84%
The government had
to nationalize it.

00:22:01.310 --> 00:22:02.090 align:middle line:90%
There's one in Italy.

00:22:02.090 --> 00:22:02.970 align:middle line:90%
I forgot what it's called.

00:22:02.970 --> 00:22:04.011 align:middle line:90%
It's a long Italian name.

00:22:04.011 --> 00:22:06.200 align:middle line:84%
It's been in the
state of what they

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.197 align:middle line:84%
call bank holiday
for two months now.

00:22:08.197 --> 00:22:09.280 align:middle line:90%
You can't get your assets.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.610 align:middle line:84%
We've seen in Russia
the largest bank

00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:14.430 align:middle line:84%
in the country, for I think
two weeks last month, stop

00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:16.030 align:middle line:84%
processing credit
cards, debit cards.

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:16.613 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:22:16.613 --> 00:22:19.300 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: So people
who relied on that

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:20.590 align:middle line:90%
couldn't pay for things.

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:22.500 align:middle line:84%
So for one, you're
assuming the banks

00:22:22.500 --> 00:22:24.150 align:middle line:90%
are going to still stay open.

00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:26.550 align:middle line:84%
And two, you're assuming
that your money in the bank,

00:22:26.550 --> 00:22:31.740 align:middle line:84%
that there won't be fees,
that they won't just

00:22:31.740 --> 00:22:34.260 align:middle line:90%
confiscate it like MF Global.

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:35.630 align:middle line:90%
Say oh, those funds.

00:22:35.630 --> 00:22:39.390 align:middle line:84%
Oh sorry, those funds
were not segregated.

00:22:39.390 --> 00:22:40.510 align:middle line:90%
JP Morgan had them.

00:22:40.510 --> 00:22:42.030 align:middle line:84%
You'll have to get
them from them.

00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:43.657 align:middle line:90%
So you're holding your money.

00:22:43.657 --> 00:22:45.490 align:middle line:84%
People hold their money
in a bank right now.

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:46.614 align:middle line:90%
You're getting no interest.

00:22:46.614 --> 00:22:49.080 align:middle line:90%
And I mean, no interest.

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:49.622 align:middle line:90%
And for what?

00:22:49.622 --> 00:22:50.871 align:middle line:90%
What are you getting for that?

00:22:50.871 --> 00:22:53.310 align:middle line:84%
You're getting it to-- you're
letting these companies who

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:54.910 align:middle line:90%
no longer are commercial banks.

00:22:54.910 --> 00:22:57.330 align:middle line:84%
Now they're just banks
that can speculate because

00:22:57.330 --> 00:22:59.440 align:middle line:90%
of the repeal of Glass Steagall.

00:22:59.440 --> 00:23:01.355 align:middle line:90%
They speculate with your money.

00:23:01.355 --> 00:23:03.730 align:middle line:84%
The government says sure,
we'll give you your money back.

00:23:03.730 --> 00:23:05.640 align:middle line:84%
But you may not get
your money back.

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:07.630 align:middle line:90%
The bank may spend it all.

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:09.620 align:middle line:90%
Or invested it all and lose it.

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:12.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So theoretically,
am I hearing this correctly,

00:23:12.730 --> 00:23:17.690 align:middle line:84%
that theoretically FDIC
extends to all banks,

00:23:17.690 --> 00:23:19.710 align:middle line:84%
including those that
would previously

00:23:19.710 --> 00:23:22.040 align:middle line:84%
have been called
investment banks?

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:24.486 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: It's a murky
line now of what is a bank

00:23:24.486 --> 00:23:25.110 align:middle line:90%
and what's not.

00:23:25.110 --> 00:23:28.640 align:middle line:84%
In fact, TARP, when
that came out in 2008,

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:30.560 align:middle line:90%
Term Asset Reduction Program.

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:32.190 align:middle line:90%
I forgot what it stands for.

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:34.760 align:middle line:84%
But it was basically just
giving money to the banks.

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:38.620 align:middle line:84%
Now two banks, Goldman
Sachs and Morgan Stanley,

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:40.660 align:middle line:84%
were considered
investment banks,

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:42.700 align:middle line:84%
which means they're
not really banks.

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:46.220 align:middle line:84%
So the government said to
them, OK, we want to save you.

00:23:46.220 --> 00:23:49.110 align:middle line:84%
So as of tomorrow,
you're a bank.

00:23:49.110 --> 00:23:52.800 align:middle line:84%
They literally overnight said,
so you're eligible for TARP.

00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:55.020 align:middle line:84%
So we'll print money
and give it to you.

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:56.670 align:middle line:90%
And yes, you're saved.

00:23:56.670 --> 00:24:00.870 align:middle line:84%
Now how did that money help
the Goldman Sachs clients?

00:24:00.870 --> 00:24:02.100 align:middle line:90%
Didn't help them any.

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:05.110 align:middle line:84%
The bank just took the money and
paid record bonuses that year,

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:06.665 align:middle line:84%
if you can believe--
record bonuses.

00:24:06.665 --> 00:24:07.540 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I remember.

00:24:07.540 --> 00:24:08.680 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: And they only
did it, because remember,

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:09.430 align:middle line:90%
that was the fall.

00:24:09.430 --> 00:24:10.760 align:middle line:90%
So that was bonus season.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:13.209 align:middle line:84%
So no one got any
money from that.

00:24:13.209 --> 00:24:15.875 align:middle line:84%
I guess you could say if you had
a brokerage account of $100,000

00:24:15.875 --> 00:24:17.917 align:middle line:90%
that it's still there.

00:24:17.917 --> 00:24:19.500 align:middle line:84%
But of course, you
lost all your money

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:22.680 align:middle line:84%
in the markets because of
Goldman Sachs recommendations.

00:24:22.680 --> 00:24:26.660 align:middle line:84%
I remember Goldman Sachs also
happened to be sued and lost,

00:24:26.660 --> 00:24:29.970 align:middle line:84%
of course it was a hand
slap, for creating securities

00:24:29.970 --> 00:24:32.670 align:middle line:84%
to sell to their clients
and then shorting them.

00:24:32.670 --> 00:24:33.822 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:24:33.822 --> 00:24:35.280 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: So that's
what you get--

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:35.920 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I mean really.

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:37.420 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: For your
SIPC protection.

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:38.810 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:41.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: This is
really criminal.

00:24:41.690 --> 00:24:44.060 align:middle line:84%
What we're talking about
is criminal behavior.

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:47.130 align:middle line:84%
Whether the government chooses
to prosecute and follow

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:49.010 align:middle line:84%
through or label it
that, it is criminal.

00:24:49.010 --> 00:24:51.840 align:middle line:84%
And when you're looking
at quantitative easing,

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:52.760 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:53.844 align:middle line:90%
I was thinking about this.

00:24:53.844 --> 00:24:55.635 align:middle line:84%
I was just trying to
get my mind around it.

00:24:55.635 --> 00:24:56.970 align:middle line:90%
Because this is not my language.

00:24:56.970 --> 00:24:58.400 align:middle line:90%
This is tricky stuff.

00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:02.540 align:middle line:84%
And I was thinking, how is,
functionally speaking, what

00:25:02.540 --> 00:25:05.940 align:middle line:84%
they did by printing money
through quantitative easing

00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:09.070 align:middle line:84%
any different than if one of us
were to counterfeit our money

00:25:09.070 --> 00:25:10.680 align:middle line:90%
and flood it into the system?

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:12.700 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: There's not
a difference at all.

00:25:12.700 --> 00:25:14.590 align:middle line:84%
And again, you're
saying it's criminal.

00:25:14.590 --> 00:25:15.970 align:middle line:90%
You wonder about the government.

00:25:15.970 --> 00:25:17.178 align:middle line:90%
Why would they let it happen?

00:25:17.178 --> 00:25:18.899 align:middle line:84%
Again, the government
and Goldman Sachs

00:25:18.899 --> 00:25:19.690 align:middle line:90%
are the same thing.

00:25:19.690 --> 00:25:20.670 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: One and the same, yes.

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:22.420 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: It's literally
the same people.

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:24.700 align:middle line:84%
You know, the head of the
Federal Reserve of New York

00:25:24.700 --> 00:25:27.882 align:middle line:84%
is the former Goldman
Chief Economist right now.

00:25:27.882 --> 00:25:29.340 align:middle line:84%
We were talking
about Robert Rubin,

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:31.920 align:middle line:84%
who was the chairman
of Goldman Sachs.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.520 align:middle line:84%
He became the Secretary of
the Treasury, Rahm Emanuel,

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:35.580 align:middle line:90%
and the list goes on.

