currencies and also

00:50:34.670 --> 00:50:38.540 align:middle line:84%
very large amounts of gold,
warehouses of the stuff.

00:50:38.540 --> 00:50:40.670 align:middle line:90%
So how does that play in?

00:50:40.670 --> 00:50:43.469 align:middle line:84%
They're obviously attempting to
make their future more secure.

00:50:43.469 --> 00:50:45.010 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well,
that's the one thing

00:50:45.010 --> 00:50:48.050 align:middle line:84%
they do have that's because
they've been selling so

00:50:48.050 --> 00:50:50.590 align:middle line:84%
many things to the
United States and Europe,

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:53.840 align:middle line:84%
they have built trillions and
trillions of currency reserves.

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:56.060 align:middle line:84%
I think it's over
$3 trillion now.

00:50:56.060 --> 00:50:58.800 align:middle line:84%
They also know that
those dollars and euros

00:50:58.800 --> 00:51:01.050 align:middle line:84%
are depreciating
because of inflation.

00:51:01.050 --> 00:51:04.460 align:middle line:84%
So not only do they have all
this depreciating currency

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:07.486 align:middle line:84%
coming in, but they fear
for what they already have.

00:51:07.486 --> 00:51:09.360 align:middle line:84%
So they have been, I
mean, buying everything.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:11.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They're buying
gold, right, gold like crazy.

00:51:11.160 --> 00:51:11.630 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Everything.

00:51:11.630 --> 00:51:12.260 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Every commodity.

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:13.050 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Everything.

00:51:13.050 --> 00:51:14.030 align:middle line:90%
They are buying gold.

00:51:14.030 --> 00:51:14.760 align:middle line:90%
They are buying--

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:15.040 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: But that's smart.

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:15.650 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Of course.

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:15.930 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That's smart.

00:51:15.930 --> 00:51:18.471 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: They know that the
dollar's going to be worthless.

00:51:18.471 --> 00:51:22.050 align:middle line:84%
And they also know that he who
has the gold makes the rules.

00:51:22.050 --> 00:51:25.220 align:middle line:84%
When this all breaks apart,
the currencies, which

00:51:25.220 --> 00:51:28.720 align:middle line:84%
could be this year, next year,
I mean two years, who knows,

00:51:28.720 --> 00:51:31.170 align:middle line:84%
whoever has the gold
is going to be rich

00:51:31.170 --> 00:51:33.240 align:middle line:84%
because there'll
be a new standard,

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:36.270 align:middle line:84%
a new kind of currency
standard based on real money.

00:51:36.270 --> 00:51:38.869 align:middle line:84%
People will look into Fort Knox,
thinking the United States is

00:51:38.869 --> 00:51:40.660 align:middle line:84%
going to be rich and
realize it's all gone.

00:51:40.660 --> 00:51:41.580 align:middle line:90%
It's been leased out.

00:51:41.580 --> 00:51:42.600 align:middle line:90%
It's been sold.

00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:45.750 align:middle line:84%
The Chinese, the
Russians, the Arabs,

00:51:45.750 --> 00:51:48.430 align:middle line:84%
basically anyone who's
had an inflow of income

00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:50.630 align:middle line:84%
has been buying them,
the gold and silver.

00:51:50.630 --> 00:51:52.060 align:middle line:84%
And they are the ones
who are going to be rich.

00:51:52.060 --> 00:51:53.990 align:middle line:84%
So the Chinese, not only
have they been buying it

00:51:53.990 --> 00:51:55.531 align:middle line:84%
for themselves, but
for years they've

00:51:55.531 --> 00:51:58.790 align:middle line:84%
been promoting, actively
promoting, for the public

00:51:58.790 --> 00:51:59.690 align:middle line:90%
to be buying it.

00:51:59.690 --> 00:52:01.506 align:middle line:84%
Because they want the
public to have gold,

00:52:01.506 --> 00:52:02.630 align:middle line:90%
too, so everyone's wealthy.

00:52:02.630 --> 00:52:04.510 align:middle line:84%
Heck, they might
confiscated it from them,

00:52:04.510 --> 00:52:06.490 align:middle line:84%
but they want to make
sure that it's in China.

00:52:06.490 --> 00:52:07.430 align:middle line:90%
Whereas in here--

00:52:07.430 --> 00:52:08.304 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's smart.

00:52:08.304 --> 00:52:11.090 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: The only promotion
we get is cash for gold.

00:52:11.090 --> 00:52:14.001 align:middle line:84%
Sell us your gold at
10 cents on the dollar.

00:52:14.001 --> 00:52:15.750 align:middle line:84%
Whereas there, they
tell them to buy gold.

00:52:15.750 --> 00:52:19.350 align:middle line:84%
Because they want the
nation to get wealthier.

00:52:19.350 --> 00:52:21.030 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well,
at least somebody

00:52:21.030 --> 00:52:23.002 align:middle line:84%
on the planet's
thinking long term.

00:52:23.002 --> 00:52:24.960 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: They definitely
got that part right.

00:52:24.960 --> 00:52:26.600 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Exactly,
which we don't.

00:52:26.600 --> 00:52:28.010 align:middle line:90%
We're not known for that.

00:52:28.010 --> 00:52:29.750 align:middle line:90%
And I wanted to ask you.

00:52:29.750 --> 00:52:31.350 align:middle line:84%
This isn't a trick
question, but I

00:52:31.350 --> 00:52:33.190 align:middle line:84%
just-- we only have
a few minutes left.

00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:35.440 align:middle line:84%
And I probably shouldn't
use our time this way.

00:52:35.440 --> 00:52:38.460 align:middle line:84%
But I've never
understood derivatives.

00:52:38.460 --> 00:52:39.840 align:middle line:84%
And I remember
watching the film,

00:52:39.840 --> 00:52:42.940 align:middle line:84%
"Inside Job," where
the question was posed,

00:52:42.940 --> 00:52:45.100 align:middle line:84%
could you please explain
derivatives to someone--

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:47.980 align:middle line:84%
I can't remember the name
the person-- very high up.

00:52:47.980 --> 00:52:49.480 align:middle line:90%
And they couldn't.

00:52:49.480 --> 00:52:50.160 align:middle line:90%
They stumbled.

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:52.030 align:middle line:84%
And finally everyone
was giggling.

00:52:52.030 --> 00:52:53.930 align:middle line:84%
And that was the end
of the conversation.

00:52:53.930 --> 00:52:56.326 align:middle line:84%
So can you explain
what a derivative is?

00:52:56.326 --> 00:52:56.950 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yes.

00:52:56.950 --> 00:52:58.450 align:middle line:84%
In the simplest
form, a derivative

00:52:58.450 --> 00:53:01.260 align:middle line:84%
just means a security that
derives its value based

00:53:01.260 --> 00:53:03.214 align:middle line:84%
on the movement of
another security.

00:53:03.214 --> 00:53:04.630 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What's
that really mean?

00:53:04.630 --> 00:53:06.379 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: Well, I
wrote a piece last year

00:53:06.379 --> 00:53:07.870 align:middle line:84%
called "The
Single-Celled Option,"

00:53:07.870 --> 00:53:10.720 align:middle line:84%
trying to say how like
you have one cell.

00:53:10.720 --> 00:53:11.650 align:middle line:90%
And then it splits.

00:53:11.650 --> 00:53:12.247 align:middle line:90%
And it splits.

00:53:12.247 --> 00:53:12.830 align:middle line:90%
And it splits.

00:53:12.830 --> 00:53:14.610 align:middle line:90%
And it becomes a whole organism.

00:53:14.610 --> 00:53:18.980 align:middle line:84%
When they created stock
options back in early '70s,

00:53:18.980 --> 00:53:22.380 align:middle line:84%
it was like OK,
you buy something.

00:53:22.380 --> 00:53:25.270 align:middle line:84%
You pay a premium,
maybe a dollar or two,

00:53:25.270 --> 00:53:29.730 align:middle line:84%
so that if a stock is
above $20 in the future,

00:53:29.730 --> 00:53:31.450 align:middle line:90%
you can get the difference.

00:53:31.450 --> 00:53:35.790 align:middle line:84%
If it's 25 and you have a
$20 call option, you make $5.

00:53:35.790 --> 00:53:37.260 align:middle line:90%
It's very simple.

00:53:37.260 --> 00:53:41.120 align:middle line:84%
So that proliferated,
because people realized

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:45.540 align:middle line:84%
they can control more capital
with a smaller investment.

00:53:45.540 --> 00:53:48.810 align:middle line:84%
The problem with the option,
though, is that it expires.

00:53:48.810 --> 00:53:50.340 align:middle line:84%
And most of them
expire worthless.

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:52.482 align:middle line:90%
So yes, you can make more money.

00:53:52.482 --> 00:53:53.690 align:middle line:90%
But you're probably instead--

00:53:53.690 --> 00:53:55.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: It can expire
at a bad time, too.

00:53:55.660 --> 00:53:55.810 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yes.

00:53:55.810 --> 00:53:56.700 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: The timing can be off.

00:53:56.700 --> 00:53:57.366 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah.

00:53:57.366 --> 00:53:59.450 align:middle line:84%
You don't know
when it-- the point

00:53:59.450 --> 00:54:01.310 align:middle line:84%
is, most people lose
money in options.

00:54:01.310 --> 00:54:03.060 align:middle line:90%
It's a loser's game, OK.

00:54:03.060 --> 00:54:06.520 align:middle line:84%
But people loved it because
Americans love leverage.

00:54:06.520 --> 00:54:08.400 align:middle line:90%
And Britons love leverage.

00:54:08.400 --> 00:54:11.010 align:middle line:84%
Everyone loves leverage
until, of course, they lose.

00:54:11.010 --> 00:54:12.790 align:middle line:84%
And when the banks
took over the system,

00:54:12.790 --> 00:54:15.130 align:middle line:84%
as I'm talking about in
the '80s and the '90s,

00:54:15.130 --> 00:54:20.260 align:middle line:84%
they created much more complex
derivatives, there's futures,

00:54:20.260 --> 00:54:24.800 align:middle line:84%
there's options, there's
collateral mortgage,

00:54:24.800 --> 00:54:28.050 align:middle line:84%
what do you call them, CMOs,
Collateral Mortgage Obligations

00:54:28.050 --> 00:54:29.650 align:middle line:84%
where they package
up real estate

00:54:29.650 --> 00:54:31.080 align:middle line:90%
and split it into pieces.

00:54:31.080 --> 00:54:32.340 align:middle line:84%
You can buy the interest
only, the property--

00:54:32.340 --> 00:54:33.580 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I've got
to say, you know

00:54:33.580 --> 00:54:35.720 align:middle line:84%
what, it's still kind of
sounding like Greek to me.

00:54:35.720 --> 00:54:37.885 align:middle line:84%
And we only have about a
minute left to wrap that up.

00:54:37.885 --> 00:54:39.343 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: And my
point is, they've

00:54:39.343 --> 00:54:43.090 align:middle line:84%
created these complex,
intertwined options, where

00:54:43.090 --> 00:54:44.180 align:middle line:90%
it's a zero sum game.

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:47.070 align:middle line:84%
Because if one person
loses, the other person

00:54:47.070 --> 00:54:48.290 align:middle line:90%
won't have money to pay them.

00:54:48.290 --> 00:54:49.050 align:middle line:90%
So everyone loses.

00:54:49.050 --> 00:54:49.865 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Everybody loses.

00:54:49.865 --> 00:54:50.180 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yes.

00:54:50.180 --> 00:54:51.420 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK, well
that sounds like that's

00:54:51.420 --> 00:54:54.190 align:middle line:84%
been the story of derivatives
from the headline news anyway.

00:54:54.190 --> 00:54:56.860 align:middle line:84%
So just to give us an
idea, and you've already

00:54:56.860 --> 00:54:59.190 align:middle line:84%
made various references
to it along the way,

00:54:59.190 --> 00:55:01.650 align:middle line:84%
but just give us a one,
two, three, four, five,

00:55:01.650 --> 00:55:03.150 align:middle line:84%
we only have a
minute or so left,

00:55:03.150 --> 00:55:05.959 align:middle line:84%
in terms of what
we can do now which

00:55:05.959 --> 00:55:08.250 align:middle line:84%
might be a little late in
the game for a lot of people,

00:55:08.250 --> 00:55:09.980 align:middle line:84%
if you haven't already
considered what's coming up.

00:55:09.980 --> 00:55:12.780 align:middle line:84%
>>HOFFMAN: If you still have
a net worth left, a liquid net

00:55:12.780 --> 00:55:16.110 align:middle line:84%
worth, I recommend putting
as much of it as possible

00:55:16.110 --> 00:55:19.070 align:middle line:84%
into physical gold and silver,
and even a little of what

00:55:19.070 --> 00:55:21.990 align:middle line:84%
they call junk silver, which is
the old dimes, because they're

00:55:21.990 --> 00:55:23.580 align:middle line:90%
a very small denomination.

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:24.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: 90% silver.

00:55:24.480 --> 00:55:25.521 align:middle line:90%
>>HOFFMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:55:25.521 --> 00:55:27.610 align:middle line:84%
That's a great way to
restore your wealth.

00:55:27.610 --> 00:55:30.080 align:middle line:84%
And also, just think about
the worst case scenario.

00:55:30.080 --> 00:55:32.720 align:middle line:84%
Forget about investment,
stocks, bonds, those things.

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:35.470 align:middle line:84%
Think what happens if
inflation gets really bad?

00:55:35.470 --> 00:55:39.130 align:middle line:84%
And that means protect
yourself with getting out

00:55:39.130 --> 00:55:41.280 align:middle line:84%
of debt for one
thing, making sure

00:55:41.280 --> 00:55:44.560 align:middle line:84%
that you have stocks of food
and other life necessities,

00:55:44.560 --> 00:55:47.120 align:middle line:84%
and of course, I can't
emphasize enough, physical gold

00:55:47.120 --> 00:55:48.830 align:middle line:90%
and silver.

00:55:48.830 --> 00:55:50.280 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I'm with you on that.

00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:52.680 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I've been following
the same strategy, and which

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:54.810 align:middle line:84%
is why I think I appreciate
your work so much,

00:55:54.810 --> 00:55:56.970 align:middle line:84%
is because from a
conservative position,

00:55:56.970 --> 00:56:00.820 align:middle line:84%
we were told back in 19--
no, back in 2006 what

00:56:00.820 --> 00:56:04.090 align:middle line:84%
would be coming down in 2008,
which everything came right

00:56:04.090 --> 00:56:05.284 align:middle line:90%
on schedule.

00:56:05.284 --> 00:56:07.700 align:middle line:84%
And so we've been thinking
about it for quite a long time.

00:56:07.700 --> 00:56:10.140 align:middle line:84%
So I'm hoping that
this has helped

00:56:10.140 --> 00:56:13.610 align:middle line:84%
you unravel some of the mystery
about the financial world a bit

00:56:13.610 --> 00:56:15.150 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:56:15.150 --> 00:56:17.680 align:middle line:10%
Even more so, I'm
hoping this conversation

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:20.610 align:middle line:10%
is giving you a little better
of an understanding of how

00:56:20.610 --> 00:56:23.472 align:middle line:10%
to take care of
you and your family

00:56:23.472 --> 00:56:25.180 align:middle line:10%
as the times go on,
because I don't think

00:56:25.180 --> 00:56:26.360 align:middle line:10%
it's going to get a lot easier.

00:56:26.360 --> 00:56:27.430 align:middle line:10%
It may get a lot worse.

00:56:27.430 --> 00:56:30.410 align:middle line:10%
And meanwhile, there
are other types

00:56:30.410 --> 00:56:32.660 align:middle line:10%
of currencies that have been
used throughout history,

00:56:32.660 --> 00:56:34.890 align:middle line:10%
one of them is known as
complimentary currencies,

00:56:34.890 --> 00:56:38.180 align:middle line:10%
to help stem some of the
problems in times like this.

00:56:38.180 --> 00:56:40.320 align:middle line:10%
And along that line, you
might enjoy my interview

00:56:40.320 --> 00:56:43.190 align:middle line:10%
with Stephen Belgin, if you
have not already watched it.

00:56:43.190 --> 00:56:46.800 align:middle line:84%
Until next time, thanks for
joining us here on Gaiam TV.

